WEBVTT

00:01.615 --> 00:03.716
<i>Jack: Over 68 million Americans</i>

00:03.718 --> 00:06.652
<i>leave the safety of
our borders every year.</i>

00:06.654 --> 00:08.054
<i>If danger strikes,</i>

00:08.055 --> 00:10.456
<i>the FBI's international response team</i>

00:10.458 --> 00:12.892
<i>is called into action.</i>

00:14.195 --> 00:17.530
[French music plays]

00:24.205 --> 00:27.406
[Indistinct conversations]

00:29.510 --> 00:32.411
Oh, you guys go ahead. I
think I'm going to walk back.

00:32.412 --> 00:33.846
- [Scoffs]
- You're crazy.

00:33.848 --> 00:36.115
You're like over a mile
from your apartment.

00:36.117 --> 00:38.117
Are we forgetting my
three-mile morning jogs?

00:38.119 --> 00:39.685
Despite what the French think,

00:39.687 --> 00:42.188
all Americans aren't fat and lazy.

00:42.190 --> 00:43.856
Sam, are you sure? It's kind of late.

00:43.858 --> 00:45.724
Ladies, we're in Paris.

00:45.726 --> 00:49.295
It's a beautiful night, and
you want to squeeze yourself

00:49.297 --> 00:52.965
onto a subway train with a car
full of <i> des étrangers?</i>

00:52.967 --> 00:54.133
Yeah.

00:54.135 --> 00:56.168
Somebody has watched "Moulin Rouge!"

00:56.170 --> 00:57.470
Way too many times!

00:57.472 --> 00:59.605
Come on! Who's coming with me?

00:59.607 --> 01:02.208
Sam, I love your bohemian soul and all,

01:02.210 --> 01:04.810
but <i> my</i> soles are hurting like hell.

01:04.812 --> 01:07.813
No way I'm walking across
town in these shoes.

01:07.815 --> 01:09.248
<i>Quel dommage.</i>

01:09.250 --> 01:10.516
[Smooches]

01:10.518 --> 01:13.452
[Chuckles]

01:13.454 --> 01:16.989
♪

01:23.631 --> 01:26.832
[Horn honks in distance]

01:27.568 --> 01:29.034
Oh. Damn it.

01:29.036 --> 01:30.269
[Groans]

01:30.271 --> 01:32.972
[Siren wails in distance]

01:32.974 --> 01:35.307
[Vehicle approaches]

01:35.309 --> 01:37.543
[Brakes squeal]

01:37.545 --> 01:40.846
<i>Mademoiselle, ça va ?</i>

01:40.848 --> 01:42.381
<i>Ça va, merci.</i> Uh...

01:42.383 --> 01:43.649
[Chuckles]

01:43.651 --> 01:46.285
I just completely forgot how
to say, "I broke my heel."

01:46.287 --> 01:47.953
<i>"J'ai cassé mon talon."</i>

01:47.955 --> 01:49.788
Of course, you speak English.

01:49.790 --> 01:51.924
<i>Un peu.</i> [French accent]
Uh, may I help you, miss?

01:51.926 --> 01:53.659
No, I'm good.

01:53.661 --> 01:55.961
Thank you. <i>Merci.</i>

01:55.963 --> 01:58.030
Well, you sure I can't offer you a ride?

01:58.032 --> 02:00.866
I can take you anywhere you like.

02:02.236 --> 02:03.569
Jack: Samantha Wade.

02:03.571 --> 02:06.105
Elementary-school teacher
from Nashville, Tennessee,

02:06.107 --> 02:08.274
found this morning
by two of her friends.

02:08.276 --> 02:10.943
Murdered and staged in the
apartment she'd been leasing

02:10.945 --> 02:12.111
for the past three weeks.

02:12.113 --> 02:14.513
Due to the brutal and provocative nature

02:14.515 --> 02:15.948
of Samantha Wade's murder,

02:15.950 --> 02:17.950
our ambassador and the
French foreign minister

02:17.952 --> 02:19.485
have requested the I.R.T.'s assistance

02:19.487 --> 02:20.920
in the homicide investigation.

02:20.922 --> 02:24.023
And given that about two million
Americans visit Paris per year,

02:24.025 --> 02:26.559
not to mention an additional
50,000 on work visas,

02:26.561 --> 02:28.027
I'd bet they'd also like us

02:28.029 --> 02:30.496
to draw up a threat
assessment to U.S. citizens.

02:30.498 --> 02:32.464
Well, there's nothing
more threatening than this.

02:32.466 --> 02:33.966
What are these things in her eyes?

02:33.968 --> 02:36.101
French investigators
have identified them

02:36.103 --> 02:37.403
as timber scribes.

02:37.405 --> 02:40.773
Bladed instruments used by land
surveyors to inscribe trees.

02:40.775 --> 02:42.942
Not exactly your go-to murder weapon.

02:42.944 --> 02:44.910
Especially in an urban environment.

02:44.912 --> 02:48.080
These tools are really
old... pre-World War I.

02:48.082 --> 02:49.982
No prints, so they're not
gonna help us narrow down

02:49.984 --> 02:51.083
our unsub's current occupation.

02:51.085 --> 02:52.318
Yeah, but these scribes

02:52.320 --> 02:53.619
aren't exactly the
murder weapons, either.

02:53.621 --> 02:54.820
I mean, even from these photos,

02:54.822 --> 02:56.088
you can see that the ocular injuries

02:56.090 --> 02:57.423
aren't her cause of death.

02:57.425 --> 02:59.792
But I don't see an official
autopsy report here, Monty.

02:59.794 --> 03:02.728
The autopsy is being
performed by the Paris Coroner

03:02.730 --> 03:04.396
as you guys sail over the Atlantic.

03:04.398 --> 03:05.998
It says here that late last night,

03:06.000 --> 03:08.067
Samantha had dinner
with the same two friends

03:08.069 --> 03:10.669
who found her this morning...
Sheila Martin and Renee Alston.

03:10.671 --> 03:11.971
According to them,

03:11.973 --> 03:14.240
she chose to walk home while
they took the Metro train.

03:14.242 --> 03:16.342
Yeah, and that was around
12:30 A.M. local time.

03:16.344 --> 03:18.544
So Samantha could have
easily been followed home.

03:18.546 --> 03:19.912
Jack: Sure.

03:19.914 --> 03:22.348
But there were not signs of
forced entry into her apartment.

03:22.350 --> 03:24.016
So it's possible that she knew

03:24.018 --> 03:25.818
or was familiar with her attacker.

03:25.820 --> 03:27.353
Except that the French investigators

03:27.355 --> 03:29.688
are interviewing all of her
known friends and associates,

03:29.690 --> 03:31.857
including Sheila and Renee.

03:31.859 --> 03:33.626
Everybody's alibi is checking out.

03:33.628 --> 03:36.462
Which means Samantha's assailant
might have presented in a way

03:36.464 --> 03:38.030
that felt comfortable to her.

03:38.032 --> 03:39.765
Well, safe enough to open the door.

03:39.767 --> 03:41.367
Clara: Well, there's
also this French saying,

03:41.369 --> 03:42.868
<i>se mettre le doigt dans l'oeil,</i>

03:42.870 --> 03:44.803
which means to put
your finger in your eye.

03:44.805 --> 03:47.306
It's the French equivalent of
putting your foot in your mouth.

03:47.308 --> 03:48.507
As in to make a mistake.

03:48.509 --> 03:49.742
A mistake that, obviously,

03:49.744 --> 03:51.243
someone felt Samantha had to pay for.

03:51.245 --> 03:52.478
Jack: Got to be more to it.

03:52.480 --> 03:54.647
I mean, this staging is so extreme.

03:54.649 --> 03:57.416
It's like he's pictured it
in his mind's eye for a while,

03:57.418 --> 03:59.285
and now he's bringing it to life.

03:59.287 --> 04:00.619
Well, if that's the case, Jack,

04:00.621 --> 04:02.187
all of this preparation and effort,

04:02.189 --> 04:03.889
he's definitely got a taste for it now.

04:03.891 --> 04:07.092
[Conversing in French]

04:11.699 --> 04:14.867
♪

04:14.869 --> 04:16.668
Bon après-midi.

04:16.671 --> 04:20.773
♪

04:25.780 --> 04:28.781
[Horn honks in distance]

04:28.783 --> 04:31.216
[Knocking on door]

04:31.218 --> 04:32.818
Just a sec!

04:32.820 --> 04:34.119
[Horn honks in distance]

04:34.121 --> 04:35.154
Qui est-ce ?

04:35.156 --> 04:36.755
Man: Pardon me, Mademoiselle.

04:36.757 --> 04:38.390
You left something behind.

04:40.828 --> 04:42.094
[Gasps]

04:42.096 --> 04:45.831
♪

04:45.833 --> 04:47.232
[Gasping]

04:47.234 --> 04:50.135
♪

04:50.137 --> 04:52.171
No, please!

04:52.173 --> 04:55.674
<i>N'ayez pas peur. Ce sera bientôt fini.</i>

04:55.676 --> 05:00.212
♪

